---
import PhotoLightbox from './PhotoLightbox.astro';
const S3 = import.meta.env.S3;
const scanAlt =
  'Black and white photo. Looking along a metro platform, with light reflecting in the tunnel and advertising along the walls. This image was captured with a scanner, and lacks any visible grain. Dark areas are too dark, with no detail to recover';
const cameraAlt =
  'Black and white photo. Looking along a metro platform, with light reflecting in the tunnel and advertising along the walls. This image was captured with a camera, and shows visible grain. Dark areas are dark, but there is detail to recover.';
const ratio = '1 / 1';
---

<figure>
  <PhotoLightbox>
    <div class="photos">
      <a
        href="#scanner-example"
        data-photo-name="scanner-example"
        data-photo-ratio={ratio}
        data-photo-alt={scanAlt}
      >
        <img
          src={`${S3}scanner-example.avif`}
          srcset={`${S3}scanner-example-2x.avif 2x, ${S3}scanner-example.avif 1x`}
          alt={scanAlt}
        />
      </a>
      <a
        href="#camera-example"
        data-photo-name="camera-example"
        data-photo-ratio={ratio}
        data-photo-alt={cameraAlt}
      >
        <img
          src={`${S3}camera-example.avif`}
          srcset={`${S3}camera-example-2x.avif 2x, ${S3}camera-example.avif 1x`}
          alt={cameraAlt}
        />
      </a>
    </div>
  </PhotoLightbox>
  <figcaption>
    We can put aside the quality of the photograph for now (it's supposed to be dark), but as a comparision
    between the scanner and the camera there is a clear difference. The scanner smooths grain and adds
    contrast, losing detail I want to preserve. Through a lot of trial and error, this was as good as I could
    get. The camera provides a much better starting point, capturing grain and detail that we can hone in the
    editing process.
  </figcaption>
</figure>

<style lang="scss">
  figure {
    container-type: inline-size;
  }
  .photos {
    display: flex;
    gap: var(--space);
    a {
      flex: 1;
      min-width: 0;
      img {
        inline-size: 100%;
      }
    }
    @container (max-width: 35rem) {
      flex-direction: column;
      align-items: center;
    }
  }
</style>
